segments.text: This is an interview with Dr. Glenn Hallmark, retired head of the Department of Electrical Engineering at Texas A&M.
Today's date is September 24, 1981.
Let's begin, Dr. Hallmark, by your telling us something about your early years in Killeen.
You were born there in 1913.
Born there in 1913 and lived, I believe, until 1920 in Killeen and then moved to Delta.
nearby until I began high school.
And then, through high school years, I lived in Houston and Waco.
What happened to you?
What was your father's occupation?
He was a cotton buyer for a major cotton exporting company.
And that's why you moved?
Uh, no.
The several moves during high school took place after my father's death.
He died about the time I started high school.
What about your mother?
Well, my mother lived until 1963.
After your father died, how did your mother support the family?
Well, we had four children, all of us, and the four children worked.
When did you start working?
No, I worked in high school.
I didn't contribute a great deal while I was in high school, but I worked in high school and college.
By that time, the other kids were older than I.
They were working and helped.
It was a family undertaking.
We all went to college.
That was not unusual in those days.
What year did your father die?
Where did you graduate from high school?
In Abilene.
What was the name of the school?
There was only one high school in Abilene, and it might have had a name, but I don't remember.
It was Abilene High School.
What year was that?
And after graduation from high school, what did you do?
Then I entered A&M.
What year?
Electrical engineering.
You got your degree, bachelor's degree at A&M?
Yes.
In what year?
Tell me about what the school was like when you were there as a student in the early 30s.
Well, A&M was a small military boys college.
I guess we had about 3,000 students during most of my time here.
This was during the well-known depression, and times were pretty hard, and so the enrollment was a little smaller, I guess, than it had been.
But it was the only kind of university, the only kind of college that I knew, so I can't compare it very much at that time with anything else.
Why did you decide to go to A&M?
because my brother went to A&M before me, I think.
How did you have an interest in electrical engineering?
How did this develop?
Oh, this developed as a child, through the years as a child, and I was very, very certain of what I wanted to do and what I was interested in.
Was electrical engineering a relatively new field when you entered it, or had it been around for a while?
No, it wasn't a new field.
I think electrical engineering
The electrical engineering department at A&M began around 1910 or 1911.
So I would consider it a new field.
Pretty well established.
One of the newer engineering fields, of course, but pretty well established.
How did the Depression affect you and your family?
I think not a great deal because the depression started two or three years after my father's death.
I think our situation didn't change as much during the depression as lots of other people.
reasonably hard time, but the older kids in the family were working.
And so that took care of the rest of us.
Was there any resentment on their part of having to work to support the rest of the family?
Probably.
Not really.
I don't think that's so...
When did you get your master's degree?
Where did you get it?
At Enid.
What did you do then after you got your bachelor's?
After I got my bachelor's degree, I worked for the city of Mahea, a little town up north.
MEXIA.
MEXIA as city engineer.
six or seven years.
And just before World War II started, I went to work for the State Parks Board as an engineer.
In Austin.
In Austin.
And then immediately after the start of World War II, someone here at the university, I think it was the head of the electrical engineering department at the university,
invited me to come back here and teach in the Naval Training School, which was a training program for electronic technicians for the Navy.
It was a pre-radar training program.
operated by the university, operated by the college before the Navy.
So I came back just very soon after the war started and began teaching in this Naval Training School.
I spent the rest of the war here.
And what about while you were in Maheo?
How was Maheo affected by the Depression?
Oh, it was hard hit.
By the Depression and every other thing you can think of, Maheo had been a hog in the town.
Beginning in 19...
and this began to play out in the late 20s just in time for the depression to start and almost finish off the town.
Does that town have a large number of Mexican Americans because of its name?
No.
It doesn't?
No.
That has nothing to do with it?
Well, the name came from
The person who received the land grant from the Mexican, from the Texas government, I guess, who was a Mexican in that area, General Mejia.
The town was named after him.
Okay.
Tell me a little something about when you were with the State Parks Board in Austin.
Well, I traveled most of the time.
At that time, primarily we were involved in maintaining the state parks and kind of mothballing them for the period of war that was coming up.
So, there wasn't much construction or planning or anything like that, but it was realized that
travel was going to be curtailed, the parks were not going to be used very much.
Some of the parks were built by the Civilian Conservation Corps, the CCC, and this was terminated.
And so much of my job was finishing up what they had left undone and getting the parks ready to ride out the period of not very much use.
Were any parks built during this time?
None were built as far as I know.
There were two or three parks under construction when the war started.
Big Bend State Park was one.
It was a state park at that time.
It's a national park now, but it was... Yeah, the Big Bend Park was under construction by the CCC camp, and when the CCC camp shut down,
They just walked off and left their tools and left everything half-finished.
And it would have been subject to a considerable deterioration without some work done on it to protect it from the other ones.
So I spent some time, I spent six weeks living down there in the Jesus Mountains at that time with my wife and my boy.
When did you marry?
Oh, in 1939.
But that job didn't last very long.
was the traveling became too much of a problem.
So I was very glad to come here to A&M and interested in some kind of teaching.
I just had a BS degree so it was equivalent to a technical institute type of program.
What year did you come back to A&M?
I believe the war started in 1941, December 1941, and I came back in 1942.
You were here throughout the war?
Yes.
Okay.
How was the school affected by World War II?
Oh, the school.
We didn't have any students.
We didn't have any civilian students.
Practically none.
And the school was maintained by this Naval Training School, which was a pretty big operation.
Two training schools.
One for electronic technicians, that's the one I was involved in.
The other was for radio operators, which was really just technical training.
We had probably, I don't remember the numbers, but we had 2,500 sailors here all the time throughout until right at the end of the war in training.
The Navy paid for their
paid the costs of their training here and I'm sure that the university, well the university did profit from this.
Well enough to pay the overhead and upkeep of the college and so forth here at this time.
These programs were supervised and run by the electrical engineering department.
I got my master's degree and left in 1946, I believe, to South Carolina.
I taught at Clemson College in South Carolina.
Clemson is a
college, very much like any of the small boys military school.
The nature of the college, just like any land grant college, taught the same programs, the same kind of school at that time.
Not quite as large, but essentially the same.
I was over there until 1950.
In what capacity?
Some level of instructor in the electrical engineering department.
I guess I was an assistant professor.
I think I was an assistant professor over there.
Clemson was very similar to A&M in its outlook and procedures.
Very similar.
Why did you leave Clemson?
get a Ph.D. a year.
I came back the end of it and got a Ph.D. in electrical engineering.
Were you one of those who were able to get a Ph.D. while they were teaching here?
Well, no, I came back with a graduate assistantship and was a graduate assistant for a couple of years and was almost through with my Ph.D.
And I believe I was offered a position on the faculty just before I got the degree.
What year did you get the education?
53, I believe.
What was the subject of your dissertation or service?
It had to do with mass spectrometry.
Would you spell that?
M-A-S-S-P-E-C-T-R-O-N-E-T-R-Y.
It's a subject.
Then you became an associate professor of electrical engineering in 1953.
I'm not quite sure of the title.
You held that position until you became department head.
Somewhere in between these times I was promoted to a professor.
When did you become department head?
I believe it was 1957.
When you became department head, about how many faculty members were under your supervision?
I think we had about 20.
Was most of the emphasis on teaching or research or a mixture?
Primarily teaching.
When did research become an important aspect of academic work?
Well, the emphasis was increased fairly steadily over this period from 19, I guess the middle 19, beginning of the 1950s.
Emphasis was increasingly put on research.
Well that's hard to say.
Well that gave a big boost to the research effort, of course.
I think emphasis was put on research because
to do this for competitive reasons with other universities.
What were some of the research endeavors that were undertaken when you were department head?
program, a beginning, beginnings of a research program in radar, weather radar, in association with Oceanography Department and Meteorology Department.

program in control systems and these were built around individuals of course individuals do research this was not something that the electrical engineering department did but we had individuals who were involved in researching control systems electromagnetic theory radiation and propagation
network theory.
These are things I remember right now.
When you were department head in the late 50s, about how many students were there in the medical engineering department?
Well, those figures could be looked up, and I don't really remember, but I expect it were four or five hundred.
When you left as department head, do you remember how much it had increased?
Yeah, it had grown some.
Well, this four or five hundred is the kind of average figure that I remember.
I guess it grew about fifty percent during the nine years that I was department head.
You were department head from 57 to 66?
Nine years, I believe.
How are the students in the late 50s and early 60s in comparison with some of the earlier students that you had been, that you had encountered?
Well, I think in the early, in the 50s we were still getting veteran students from World War II who were very serious.
dedicated students.
That is, they knew what they wanted to do and they had goals and they stuck with those goals.
About in the late 50s, the nature of the students changed some because we got less of these veteran students and more youngsters just out of high school.
And about that time, I think the quality of the high school students began to improve some.
So there was a difference in maturity.
This is about the only thing I can remember.
They were younger and they did not have as well-defined goals in what they were.
but I think we always got pretty capable students.
I don't have much, I don't want to say anything that detracts from the capability of the students we had.
While you were in the department, were there ever any women students in Electrical Engineering?
Well, in the latter year, in the last year or two,
We had one or two.
They were just beginning.
Most of the years, women weren't allowed to enroll in that.
And I think we did have one or two women teachers, but women weren't allowed to enroll in it, too.
Sometime, like the mid-60s, I've forgotten how to tell you for sure.
We did have one or two.
After you stepped down as department head in 1966 and stayed on until 1976 when you retired.
While you were in the department, were there any very many flags that drove an electable Indian hearing?
Well, not any significant numbers, maybe one or two while I was department head.
But after that time in the 70s, we had several.
Not a big percentage, but we had several.
Why do you think that there have been revenue blacks who have enrolled in any aspect of engineering?
You don't really want me to answer that, do you?
No, you don't.
Well, let's strike that for the record.
Okay, have electrical engineers always commanded the high salary levels that they do today?
In a relative way, yeah.
As long as I can remember, electrical engineers have had a little bit higher beginning salaries than average for engineering.
And this goes back as far as I can remember.
Have there ever been any years in which there were rather few jobs for electrical engineers?
Oh, yeah, when I graduated in the 30s.
Back in the 30s.
Except for that, they've always had good selections.
I believe that's correct.
Probably.
More than half the class when I graduated in those years did not go into the field of electrical engineering.
Some field allied to electrical engineering maybe, but there weren't very many jobs in the engineering area in the 30's.
Of course the war changed over there.
Let's discuss the faculty when you were department head.
Was there a feeling of camaraderie among the faculty members?
Very much.
It was a close-knit family.
Do you think this has changed over the years?
Yes, it's changed over the years.
The department has gotten much bigger, a different kind of faculty, and it has changed very much.
At the time I was department head, the faculty had not had any great growth, and most of us had worked together for a good many years.
I had been here several years, was here as a student, and so we were close in that group.
these faculty members under your program supervision, what were some of the schools that they had come from?
Oh, that's hard for me to remember.
We had a larger than would be desirable number of A&M graduates, but we had graduates from Cornell,
Clemson in South Carolina.
One of the universities in North Carolina, I've forgotten which one.
Several who did undergraduate work.
Now these are newer faculty members that joined the faculty in the 50s and the 60s.
who did undergraduate work here and then went to other universities for graduate study, Wisconsin, Illinois.
Let's see, we had one of our faculty members from Purdue, University of Texas.
A mixture of schools, many of them were schools in the South,
You've seen a number of, since you've been at A&M, you've seen a number of different governors in Texas.
Have there been any difference in some of these governors in regard to the degree of support they've given A&M?
Well I couldn't answer that because I never was at a level in the university that had any dealings with the governor or the legislature.
Yeah, I think we were, I think we were
in the upper ranks of the electrical engineering departments in the south, not at the top of the upper ranks.
What were some of the other students in those upper ranks?
Well, I mentioned University of Texas, Georgia Tech, Rice.
I can think of some more.
And I feel like we were not quite at the level of those schools.
Facilities and faculty and program, these kinds of things.
And why did you step down as a department?
Because of ill health.
And you stayed on for 10 more years as a professor?
Yeah.
The ill health of the dean said I made him sick.
While you were still in the department, as a professor, the Vietnam War was underway.
Could you say how any of this affected Texas A&M?
I don't think it had very much effect on Texas A&M.
There was of course a reduction in students because of the large number involved in the war, but we didn't grow much and we didn't lose much during the Vietnam War.
The biggest impact of the Vietnam War was dissension on campuses over the country and we had very little of that here.
Why do you suppose that happened?
It's the nature of the Vietnam War.
and I think good administration of the university at that time.
Were there any other universities in Texas that had any problems on campuses during the Vietnam War?
As I remember, there were some demonstrations and some problems at other universities.
But there weren't, to your knowledge, there weren't even any demonstrations that they had?
I can't remember anything that I'd seriously consider a demonstration.
How did the university change when you retired in 1976 compared to when you became a full-time personnel and teaching back in 1953?
During those 23 years, what was something wrong?
How had the university changed?
Well, before I retired A&M had begun admitting women and had made ROTC optional, but not very long before.
And these were just beginning to have an impact on the university when I retired.
And over the next ten years they have a tremendous impact on the university.
character of the university.
What about the quality of students?
By the early and mid seventies, how did they contrast with the previous quality of students?
Well, I think the students were a better group of fellows, increasingly better as time went on.
From the time I began to
know something about their background and records.
What do you think that is when the public has an image that the quality of students has steadily decreased over the years?
Well perhaps there are two reasons for that.
One is I think the public's perception might not be correct and the other is I think our higher
the quality of students that came to A&M improved over the years relative to general development.
In other words, many of these slower learners didn't come to A&M.
I expect this is so.
Well, I know that our admissions raised the quality of the students over this period.
We got better.
with better backgrounds.
Increasingly as time went on, probably this is still increasing now.
What were some of the research endeavors in mechanical engineering at the time you were retiring in the mid-seventies and running away at the time?
I guess the biggest research effort was in semiconductor devices.
general area of transistors and applications of these things that were beginning in the late, beginning with us in the Middle 60s and have continued on since then.
We had started a research program funded principally by Texas Instruments in this area
sort of in its beginning stages when I was replaced and has increased importantly since then.
This has been a big thing, you know, the last 20 years.
Have you remained professionally active since you retired in 1976?
Not really.
My interest has been a hobby interest since I retired.
In what capacity?
Oh, I'm a ham radio operator and I'm a computer buff.
These are areas that I was interested in throughout my professional career as they came along.
You've been retired for five years.
What are some of the things you've done to keep busy besides these two particular hobbies?
That keeps me busy.
Those are pretty, those are hobbies that one can spend as much time as you want to and put it off when you need to.
Do you have any regrets about your career at Texas A&M?
I enjoyed it thoroughly.
I think it's wonderful.
Would you have done anything differently if you had it to do over?
Well, if I could start it over again at 68 years old, I'd know some things to do differently.
As I went along, I did the things that I thought were the right thing.
I might still think they were the right thing.
Do you ever run across any of your former students?
Oh, yeah.
Any place you go in the state, some of the other professors have said that no matter where they go, they run across the former students.
Most places you go, you do, if you're there very long, you run across somebody.
I run across more of them who just stop by occasionally, passing through here.
Many of them do, some of them do.
Do you think whether the student was smaller than the faculty members or more personal interest in the students than they have since they became a larger university?
Well yes, I expect that's true.
I think you would expect that.
Certainly we knew our students better than we do now.
What about your children?
Did you have a son?
We have one son, yes.
Where does he live?
He's in Phoenix, in the Phoenix area.
In what capacity?
He works for computer companies out there.
And like lots of these people, he changes around from one to another.
Is there anything else we need to touch on?
Any observations you had about your career?
Oh, I can't, you asked me if I'd enjoyed my time here at A&M, I think, and I have tremendously.

I think it was a fine career, but I think I, I feel like I lived in the golden age of my career, and looking back at the things that have happened during, well, from the time I graduated college until now, you can't believe
advances that have taken place, the rapidity with which these advances have taken place, and things that to me just seem absolutely wonderful.
Starting with the development of, pretty much the development of radio communication in the 1930s, and the great strides that were made during World War II
communications and electronic devices during that time, which later were applied to civilian use.
Development of television in the 50s, primarily, and beginning in 1948.
Announcement or discovery of the transistor by Bell Laboratories.
This revolutionized the whole electrical industry.
30 years.
Progress made strides that took us 50 years up until that time.
All these things, all these things now since 1950 that depend on applications and offshoots of the transistor
Absolutely new to us old guys, you know, school before that time.
But I think it's been tremendous and exciting and fun to keep up with.
And you can believe this because this is now my hobby after I retired from this career.
I still find it fascinating and hard to believe.
Thank you very much for taking the time to talk with me.
You bet.
Glad you came by.
